gap analysis (artifact: warp_reduce_sum.sm_80.ptx):

  G1. `gpu_warp_shuffle_xor(v, mask)` — builtin NOT WIRED.
      PTX line 78: `// RFC 055 055-P0 - unsupported call: gpu_warp_shuffle_xor`
      compiler/codegen/nvptx_target.hexa wires only `gpu_warp_shuffle(v, lane)`
      (shfl.sync.idx.b32, idx-mode source-lane select). The XOR butterfly
      variant `shfl.sync.bfly.b32` is documented in PTX ISA §9.7.13.4 but
      not yet emitted. Additionally the existing builtin returns u32 only
      (`.b32`) — FP64 shuffle would require composing 2× 32-bit halves
      (high/low) and reassembling on the recv side. Both extensions are
      compiler-source-touching follow-on cycles (out of N70 scope per
      task spec).
      Consequence in PTX: line 79 reads %fd18 which is never assigned →
      garbage FP64 accumulates into %fd9 each loop iteration.

  G2. integer `/` binop — NOT WIRED (or wired only for ad-hoc cases).
      3 occurrences: line 81 (`mask / 2`), line 85 (`tid / 32`),
      line 89 (`tid / 32`) — all emit `// unsupported binop: /`.
      Lines 82, 86, 89/90 reference %rd20/%rd21/%rd25 which never receive
      a value. The PTX assembler accepts (declarations exist), but at
      runtime the values are undefined garbage.
      Consequence: `mask > 0` predicate on line 74 likely stays true
      forever (garbage retained in %rd16 because `mov.u64 %rd16, %rd20`
      where %rd20 was never written) → kernel hangs.

  Note: N64 (single-thread reduce_sum) closed STMT_LOAD/STORE + cmp +
  bounds-check + i64-classifier (5 gaps in commit `2a1eaed0`). The new
  N70 gaps (gpu_warp_shuffle_xor + `/`) are ORTHOGONAL — none of N64's
  fixes overlap.


